title.narrative: MNCH, EPI, Prevention of Mother to Child Transmission of HIV (PMTCT)

description.narrative: By 2022, national and sub national health care institutions and front-line health workers have improved capacity to reach more vulnerable populations with quality immunization and Maternal, Neonatal, and Child Health (MNCH) (including PMTCT) services in at least four most deprived States/Regions and in conflict, disaster affected and peri-urban areas in Yangon, which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care (Covid), Operations Support To Programme Delivery, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2022, more children under 5 and women of reproductive age equitably access and utilize evidence-based health, HIV & nutrition interventions, including adoption of key behaviours, especially among vulnerable populations in most deprived states/regions, conflict-affected and peri-urban areas (Goal Area 1 UNICEF Strategic Framework 2018-2021)
